  "text": "except relative to a rival set of forecasts or a benchmark. Any one of a number of time-series models, or more structural models, could be used to generate forecasts for this purpose, but would be unlikely to pose a particularly stern test unless they adequately captured the dramatic slowdown in inflation rates to the historically low rates observed over the last ten years: see figure 1. According to the arguments in [CITATION_1] it might be thought hard to beat a 'no change' forecast. 12 In fact we record the MSFE which uses the unconditional mean of inflation over the forecast period as a benchmark. This is a cheat in that it uses information that would not have been available at the time the forecast was made, but is handicapped by not being able to exploit any temporal dependence in the inflation series.",
